# Step 1g: Check for presence of missing values in the dataset.

def missing_check(dataframe1):
    total = dataframe1.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending=False)   # total number of null values
    percent = (dataframe1.isnull().sum()/dataframe1.isnull().count()).sort_values(ascending=False)  # percentage of values that are null
    missing_data = pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Total', 'Percent'])  # putting the above two together
    return missing_data 
    # return the dataframe
missing_check(data)

# Representation of spread of ratings as given by users.

quantiles = data.groupby('userId')['ratings'].count().sort_values(ascending=False).quantile(np.arange(0,1.01,0.01), interpolation='higher')
plt.figure(figsize=(10,10))
plt.title("Quantiles and their Values")
quantiles.plot()
# quantiles with 0.05 difference
plt.scatter(x=quantiles.index[::5], y=quantiles.values[::5], c='orange', label="quantiles with 0.05 intervals")
# quantiles with 0.25 difference
plt.scatter(x=quantiles.index[::25], y=quantiles.values[::25], c='m', label = "quantiles with 0.25 intervals")
plt.ylabel('No of ratings by user')
plt.xlabel('Value at the quantile')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.show()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(2,figsize=(15,15))
chart=sns.barplot(x="unique_product_id", y="avg_rating", data=popularity_recommendation_dataframe.iloc[10:20],ax=ax[0])
for p in chart.patches:
  chart.annotate(format(p.get_height(), '.2f'), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 10), textcoords = 'offset points')
chart1=sns.barplot(x="unique_product_id", y="number_of_reviews", data=popularity_recommendation_dataframe.iloc[10:20],ax=ax[1])
for p in chart1.patches:
  chart1.annotate(format(p.get_height(), '.2f'), (p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2., p.get_height()), ha = 'center', va = 'center', xytext = (0, 10), textcoords = 'offset points')
chart1.set_xticklabels(rotation=30,labels=popularity_recommendation_dataframe.iloc[10:20,0].values)
chart.set_xticklabels(rotation=30,labels=popularity_recommendation_dataframe.iloc[10:20,0].values)
print()

# SVD/ Matrix Factorization method.......................
from surprise import SVD
from surprise.model_selection import cross_validate
from surprise import Reader
from surprise import Dataset

from surprise import accuracy
from surprise import KNNWithMeans

reader = Reader(rating_scale=(1, 5))
surprise_data = Dataset.load_from_df(dataframe3, reader)
trainset, testset = train_test_split(surprise_data, test_size=.3)



    













In [61]:



    


# Step 5:- Build Collaborative Filtering model 
# Step 6:- Evaluate the above model. ( Once the model is trained on the training data, it can be used to compute the error (like RMSE) on predictions made on the test data.) You can also use a different method to evaluate the models



    













In [63]:



    


# Singular Value Decomposition Algorithm used for creating a recommendation system   
algo = SVD()
algo.fit(trainset)
predictions = algo.test(testset)
# Then compute RMSE
accuracy.rmse(predictions, verbose=True)
accuracy.mse(predictions, verbose=True)
accuracy.mae(predictions, verbose=True)
accuracy.fcp(predictions, verbose=True)
print()



    















    






RMSE: 0.8563
MSE: 0.7332

FCP:  0.6200




















In [64]:



    


# Created a user based collaborative filtering model

algo = KNNWithMeans(k=50, sim_options={'name': 'pearson_baseline', 'user_based': True})
algo.fit(trainset)
# run the trained model against the testset
test_pred_user = algo.test(testset)
# get RMSE
print("User-based Model : Test Set")
accuracy.rmse(test_pred_user, verbose=True)
accuracy.mse(test_pred_user, verbose=True)
accuracy.mae(test_pred_user, verbose=True)
accuracy.fcp(test_pred_user, verbose=True)
print()

In [65]:



    


# Created an item based collaborative filtering model
algo = KNNWithMeans(k=50, sim_options={'name': 'pearson_baseline', 'user_based': False})
algo.fit(trainset)
# run the trained model against the testset
test_pred_item = algo.test(testset)
# get RMSE
print("Item-based Model : Test Set")
accuracy.rmse(test_pred_item, verbose=True)
accuracy.mse(test_pred_item, verbose=True)
accuracy.mae(test_pred_item, verbose=True)
accuracy.fcp(test_pred_item, verbose=True)
print()

    item_colabarative_recommednation_dataframe.append([test_pred_item[i].uid,test_pred_item[i].iid,test_pred_item[i].r_ui,test_pred_item[i].est,test_pred_item[i].details['actual_k'],test_pred_item[i].details['was_impossible']])

    item_colabarative_recommednation_dataframe.append([test_pred_item[i].uid,test_pred_item[i].iid,test_pred_item[i].r_ui,test_pred_item[i].est,test_pred_item[i].details['reason'],test_pred_item[i].details['was_impossible']])

# Insights:- 

# 1. Insight 1:- 
# The popularity based recommendation system recommends products based on the highest average rating of the products.
# The collaborative filtering technique uses relationship between items and users to predict products.
# Both the models User based collaborative filtering and item based collaborative filtering seem to work equally good on the dataset.
# The RMSE score for both is around 0.98 indicating low error value.
# But the item based collabrative model works better marginally.

# Code for plotting distplots for feature variables.
fig,ax = plt.subplots(2,2,figsize=(10,10))
c1=0
c2=0
flag=0
for i in range(1,5): 
  sns.distplot(item_recommendation_dataframe.iloc[i,1:],ax=ax[c1,c2])
  ax[c1,c2].set_xlabel(item_recommendation_dataframe.iloc[i,0])
  if flag==0:
    c1=c1+1
    c1=c1%2
    flag=1
  else:
    c2=c2+1
    c2=c2%2
    flag=0
